'inputText': 'Ashtarte Chapter 75: Ashtarte, a popular fantasy romance manhwa, has been adapted into a webtoon on Naver Webtoon. The tale revolves around Princess Ashtarte, ostracized for her black hair, considered a bad omen in the Firenze Empire. Branded as the prophesied harbinger of darkness, she encounters Liana, a mysterious silver-haired girl claiming to be her guardian angel. Together, they embark on a journey to unveil the truth behind the prophecy and their destinies. The webtoon has garnered praise for its engaging plot, exquisite art, and endearing characters. Chapter 74, released on December 25, 2023, heightened anticipation for the next installment. Here’s what you need to know about Ashtarte Chapter 75: Ashtarte Chapter 75 is set to release on January 12, 2024, at 10:00 AM China Standard Time (CST) or 10:00 am, in Washington, DC, USA (IST). Readers can access it on platforms like Naver Webtoon, Tappytoon, and MangaToon. The main characters include: Ashtarte: The black-haired princess of the Firenze Empire, kind and loyal, bearing a hidden power linked to the world-ending prophecy. Liana: A silver-haired mystery, claiming to be Ashtarte’s guardian angel, with a cheerful demeanor concealing a mysterious identity tied to world salvation. Leon: Ashtarte’s ambitious older brother, the prince of the Firenze Empire, intent on capturing Ashtarte and Liana for his purposes. Rin: Ashtarte’s childhood friend and loyal servant, sweet and optimistic, harboring a crush on Ashtarte. Set in a world of magic and prophecy, Ashtarte unfolds in the powerful yet troubled Firenze Empire. A prophecy predicts the world’s end at the hands of a black-haired princess, isolating Ashtarte. When she meets Liana, who claims she is a blessing, their journey to uncover the truth begins. Pursued by Leon, they face challenges, enemies, and allies, developing a deep bond and a romantic relationship. While there’s no official trailer for Ashtarte Chapter 75, previews and teasers can be expected on Naver Webtoon’s official social media accounts and the author’s platform. Previous chapters and trailers can be viewed on Naver Webtoon, Tappytoon, and MangaToon. Ashtarte Chapter 75 marks the webtoon’s conclusion, confirmed by the author. Grateful for fans’ support, the author promised a satisfying ending. Hints of a sequel or spin-off have been dropped, heightening excitement and anxiety among fans about Ashtarte and Liana’s fate and the prophecy’s resolution. 5 Example video title will go here for this video BOISE, Idaho — A motion was filed on behalf of Idaho's longest death row inmate to the Idaho Supreme Court to stay his execution, according to newly filed court documents. The Motion to Stay Execution of Thomas Creech was filed Wednesday. According to court documents, a date is set for oral arguments on Monday, Feb. 5. Both sides will be given five minutes to present their arguments against or in support of the appeal. Attorneys for Creech also filed a brief in support of the stay in his execution. As previously reported by KREM, a death warrant for Thomas Creech was filed in Ada County District Court on Tuesday, Jan. 30. According to the warrant, the 74-year-old convicted murderer will be executed on Feb. 28, 2024. The warrant did not say how or what time Creech will be executed. The Idaho Department of Corrections said in a news release last October that they have obtained the chemicals necessary to carry out an execution by lethal injection. As KTVB previously reported, on Jan. 25, Creech was identified as a suspect in a cold case murder in California from nearly 50 years ago. According to the San Bernardino County Sheriff's Department, Daniel Walker was shot multiple times by a suspect who woke him up while sleeping in a parked van alongside Interstate 40 on Oct. 1, 1974. Walker's passenger escaped and was able to get the attention of a passing driver. Walker was eventually taken to an area hospital, where he later died. In 1983, Creech pleaded guilty to first-degree murder for killing a fellow inmate in 1981 while he was already in prison. He was sentenced to death.
